{
  "agent": "claude",
  "round": 1,
  "verdict": "REQUEST_CHANGES",
  "objections": [
    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "artifact:execution-order",
      "description": "The execution plan has no acceptance criteria, no timebox estimates, and no dependency graph between steps. Step 1 ('define design tokens') is unbounded — teams burn weeks here without shipping anything. Step 2 ('refactor app shell, home, and search header') is actually 3 separate workstreams bundled into one step. Step 4 ('redesign document viewer') is the highest-value item for a reading app but is sequenced 4th, after cosmetic shell work. This ordering optimizes for visual polish over core user value.",
      "suggested_fix": "Reorder: (1) Document viewer reading ergonomics first — this is the product's core loop and where users spend 80% of time. (2) Search result density and filter interactions — this is the acquisition loop. (3) Design tokens and shell coherence — extract tokens FROM the viewer/search work, not before it. (4) Home/dashboard. (5) Bottom sheet standardization. (6) Analytics. Each step needs: a definition of done, max timebox in days, and explicit list of files/components touched."
    },
    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "artifact:document-viewer",
      "description": "For a DOU (Diário Oficial da União) reading app, the document viewer section is dangerously underspecified. DOU documents are dense legal/regulatory text — often 5,000-50,000+ words, heavily structured with articles, paragraphs, incisos, and alíneas. The plan mentions 'reading typography' and 'section jumps' but says nothing about: (1) How nested legal hierarchies are rendered and navigated, (2) How cross-references within a document are resolved (e.g., 'conforme o Art. 5° da Lei 8.666'), (3) How search term highlighting persists during reading, (4) How the TOC is generated from real DOU structure vs generic heading extraction, (5) Keyboard/swipe navigation between sections on mobile, (6) Offline reading or progressive loading for massive documents, (7) Font size / line height user controls — essential for legal reading.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add a dedicated 'Document Viewer UX Specification' sub-section that addresses: legal hierarchy rendering (indented tree vs flat with markers), intra-document anchor linking, search-term-in-context highlighting that survives scroll, TOC generation strategy keyed to DOU document schema (not generic HTML headings), progressive rendering for documents over 10k words, and user-controlled typography settings (font size, line spacing, width). This is the product — it cannot be a bullet point."
    },
    {
      "severity": "high",
      "location": "artifact:search",
      "description": "The search section mentions 'backend-inferred filters' and 'corpus facets' but doesn't specify what the backend actually returns today. If gabi-es (the Elasticsearch MCP) doesn't already return faceted aggregations for organ, type, section, and date range, then the entire filter UX is speculative. The plan needs to distinguish between 'UX for capabilities that exist' vs 'UX that requires backend changes' — otherwise the frontend team builds filter shells with no data to populate them.",
      "suggested_fix": "Audit gabi-es response schema now. Document which aggregations/facets are available today. Split search UX into two tiers: Tier 1 uses only currently-available backend capabilities (likely: keyword search, date filtering, basic type). Tier 2 requires backend work (faceted counts, query interpretation, zero-result suggestions). Sequence Tier 1 first."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "artifact:visual-direction",
      "description": "'Editorial and institutional dark theme with stronger typography, warmer neutrals, restrained accent usage' is mood-board language, not engineering specification. What typeface? What scale? What neutral palette (warm gray toward what hue — amber? rose? ochre?)? What accent color replaces purple, and at what usage frequency? Without these decisions locked, every component PR becomes a design debate.",
      "suggested_fix": "Commit to specifics: (1) Pick a typeface stack — e.g., Inter for UI, Literata or Source Serif for document reading. (2) Define the neutral scale with actual HSL values — e.g., base gray at hsl(30, 5%, X%) for warm. (3) Pick one accent hue with 3 shades. (4) Define the type scale (8 sizes, specific rem values, line heights). Put this in a design-tokens.ts file as the first deliverable, not a Figma exploration."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "artifact:bottom-sheets",
      "description": "Plan says 'standardize snapping behavior and action density' but doesn't address the hard UX problems with bottom sheets in reading contexts: (1) How does a TOC bottom sheet interact with scroll position — does selecting a section dismiss the sheet AND scroll, or keep it open at a smaller snap point? (2) What's the gesture conflict resolution between pull-to-dismiss on the sheet and scroll within the sheet content? (3) On sheets with both filters and action buttons, what's the z-order — are CTAs pinned to sheet bottom or do they scroll? These are the decisions that make sheets feel premium vs janky.",
      "suggested_fix": "Define three bottom sheet variants with explicit behaviors: (1) Selector sheet (TOC, filter pickers): snaps to 40%/85%, selecting an item dismisses to 0% and triggers navigation. (2) Editor sheet (multi-filter editing, saved search config): snaps to 60%/95%, has a sticky footer with Apply/Reset, internal scroll is independent. (3) Action sheet (share, bookmark, report): snaps to auto-height only, no internal scroll. Document gesture precedence: sheet drag wins over internal scroll when touch starts on handle zone (top 48px); internal scroll wins otherwise."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "artifact:dashboard-home",
      "description": "'Resumed reading, saved searches, corpus coverage, and live slices' implies persistent user state (reading position, saved queries), but there's no mention of where this state lives. Is there a backend user service? LocalStorage? Is the user even authenticated? If this is unauthenticated, localStorage is the only option and 'corpus coverage' becomes a static stat, not personalized. This changes the entire home page design.",
      "suggested_fix": "State the auth model. If unauthenticated: home shows recent reading history (localStorage), trending/recent DOU publications, and quick corpus stats. If authenticated: add saved searches, reading lists, and personalized coverage. Design the unauthenticated version first — it's the default experience and shouldn't feel degraded."
    },
    {
      "severity": "medium",
      "location": "artifact:mcp-usage",
      "description": "MCP tool usage is listed but not mapped to execution steps. 'json-render for quick prototype validation of search-to-viewer flows' — when? During step 2? Step 3? 'gabi-es for corpus-grounded search/viewer/filter UX' — this should be step 0, not a floating reference. Without mapping tools to steps, they become aspirational rather than operational.",
      "suggested_fix": "Map each MCP tool to specific execution steps: gabi-es → pre-step-1 schema audit + step 2 search capability assessment. ui-copilot → steps 1, 3, 4 for component selection. json-render → step 3 result card prototyping, step 4 viewer layout prototyping. Make the gabi-es audit a blocking prerequisite for the search step."
    },
    {
      "severity": "low",
      "location": "artifact:analytics",
      "description": "'De-prioritize visual polish there until real backend-driven analytics are available' is correct directionally but too vague. Does 'de-prioritize' mean don't touch it, hide it, or remove it from nav? A half-built analytics page that ships hurts perceived quality more than no analytics page.",
      "suggested_fix": "Remove analytics from the navigation entirely. Add a feature flag. When backend analytics endpoints exist, re-enable. Don't ship placeholder pages in a premium product."
    }
  ],
  "suggestions": [
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "artifact:document-viewer",
      "description": "Add a 'reading mode' toggle that strips sidebar chrome and maximizes content width on tablet/desktop. On mobile, this is the default. Include a persistent floating progress indicator (thin bar or percentage) that doesn't consume vertical space but gives spatial awareness in long documents."
    },
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "artifact:search",
      "description": "Define the empty state and first-visit experience explicitly. When a user opens the app for the first time with no search history, what do they see? Trending DOU topics? Today's publications? A prominent search prompt? This is the most common state for new users and it's unaddressed."
    },
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "artifact:cross-cutting",
      "description": "Add a performance budget section. Mobile-first dark-first means likely constrained devices. Set targets: LCP < 1.5s, bundle size < 200kb gzipped for initial route, search results render < 300ms after network response. These constraints will drive real architecture decisions (e.g., virtualized lists for results, lazy-loaded document sections)."
    },
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "artifact:cross-cutting",
      "description": "Address accessibility. Dark-first is fine, but WCAG AA contrast ratios on warm neutrals are notoriously hard to hit. The design token step must include contrast validation. Also: bottom sheets need proper focus trapping and screen reader announcements. Legal document reading must support screen readers — this is a government data product."
    },
    {
      "type": "improvement",
      "location": "artifact:document-viewer",
      "description": "Consider URL-driven deep linking into document sections. For a legal/regulatory reading app, the ability to share a link to a specific article within a DOU publication is a high-value professional feature. This requires a defined URL schema (e.g., /document/:id#section-:sectionId) and server-side or client-side scroll-to behavior."
    }
  ],
